This raises the chances of a sharp snapback - but I am uncertain from what level. No one can be certain.

The ten year US note yield just broke 2.80% to the downside. The yield is down by six basis points - perhaps supportive of my view that today's selling is importantly a function of derisking of vol and risk parity strategies coupled with some margin calls.

Misguided business media is focus on interest rates. They are not even paying attention to the fact that 10 year yield has hit a day's low and is five basis points down from Friday! The problem is market structure and the dominance of short vol and risk parity

One of these days the sort of selective marketing we see every day in the biz media - that emphasizes the positives and deemphasizes the negatives - will end up with broad SEC evaluation, fines and censures.
A constant refrain - a two crowded side of a boat inhabited by short vol and risk parity strategies - may be producing a derisking and the selling we are witnessing today .

However, with stocks making new lows the message to me is that the responsible actor is a dangerous shift in the market's structure - fully discussed in this morning's two part opening missive - that is determining market price action.

@TSTRealMoneyPro Interestingly the yield on the ten year US note is at the day's lows - at 2.823%, its three basis points lower this afternoon. If stocks were moving lower (Friday and today) only because of higher interest rates - stocks would have likely stabilized today.
@CNBCFastMoney should be addressing the dangerous shift in market structure which likely is exacerbating the market decline. Less first level thinking, more second level thinking... respectfully.
